{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-95d0bceb6237e8a8", "type": "tool_result", "content": "0\tRPPNET: PERCEPTUALLY-GROUPED RHYTHM-PITCH PRIMITIVES\n1\tFOR LONG-TERM STRUCTURE MELODY GENERATION VIA\n2\tBOUNDARY-AWARE MODELING\n3\tTieyao Zhang1\n4\tYuke Liu1\n5\tJiaxing Yu2\n6\t2\n7\t2\n8\tXinda Wu\n9\tKejun Zhang\n10\tGenfang Chen1,3\n11\t1\n12\tZhejiang Conservatory of Music, Hangzhou, China\n13\t2\n14\tZhejiang University, Hangzhou, China\n15\t3\n16\tZJU-ZJCM MusicAI Lab, Hangzhou, China\n17\ttieyaozhang@stu.zjcm.edu.cn, keke@stu.zjcm.edu.cn, yujx@zju.edu.cn,\n18\twuxinda@zju.edu.cn, zhangkejun@zju.edu.cn, cgf@zjcm.edu.cn\n19\t\n20\tarXiv:2607.19776v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n21\t\n22\tABSTRACT\n23\t\n24\tThey require no hand-crafted domain rules and can automatically extract knowledge from large-scale data; their\n25\teffectiveness has been validated across multiple disciplines\n26\t[6–10].\n27\tHowever, long-term structure modeling in symbolic\n28\tmusic remains challenging [11–13]. Existing methods\n29\toperate within linear sequence frameworks where attention mechanisms capture long-range token correlations yet\n30\tfail to learn explicit associations between non-adjacent\n31\tbut functionally similar structural units; meanwhile, this\n32\ttask requires integrating music theory, computational modeling, psychology, and neuroscience [14]. Both factors\n33\tjointly constrain effective learning of hierarchical logic, biasing models toward local statistical patterns and limiting\n34\tlong-term structure generation quality.\n35\tRecent works integrate computational modeling with\n36\tmusic theory to improve long-term coherence through explicit structural boundaries and thematic features, such as\n37\tMuseformer [15] with its hierarchical attention mechanism, Theme Transformer [16] with thematic material retrieval, and MELONS [17] and PopMNet [18] with graphstructured thematic variation encoding. However, these\n38\tmethods rely on fixed bar-level units. Psychological evidence shows that listeners perceive structural boundaries\n39\tthrough acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similaritybased grouping [19–21], rather than fixed metric segmentation. This mismatch hinders listeners’ perceptual grouping of the generated structure, thereby reducing overall\n40\tmusical coherence.\n41\tTo address this problem, we propose a hierarchical\n42\tmelody generation framework, RPPNet 1 . It is based on\n43\tan autoregressive architecture and splits generation into\n44\tan RPP-level generation stage and a Note-level generation stage. Both stages use a Transformer encoder-decoder\n45\t[22].\n46\tDrawing on music theory and cognitive psychology,\n47\twe use three perceptual dimensions—acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity relations—and rhythmic structure analysis [20, 23, 24] to design a heuristic algorithm.\n48\t\n49\tExisting symbolic music generation models typically use\n50\tbars as the basic structural unit. However, human perception of musical phrases often does not align with notated\n51\tbar lines, leading to long-term structural fragmentation.\n52\tThis paper proposes RPPNet—a two-stage deep learning\n53\tarchitecture with variable structural boundaries. It first\n54\tgenerates variable-length Rhythm-Pitch Primitive (RPP)\n55\tsequences, where each RPP encodes note count, rhythm,\n56\tand contour; then decodes the RPP sequences into concrete notes. The grouping of RPPs is automatically derived\n57\tfrom acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity perception based on music psychology. Experiments show that\n58\tmelodies generated by RPPNet are superior in both longterm structure and musicality, with significant improvements across all subjective evaluation dimensions. Ablation studies confirm that the performance gain stems from\n59\tthe structural correctness of the psychological representation, rather than from model capacity. This work offers\n60\tan interdisciplinary perspective for music generation, integrating music theory, computational modeling, and music\n61\tpsychology.\n62\t1. INTRODUCTION\n63\tSymbolic melody generation is a core direction of generative AI in art [1]. In recent years, text-to-audio models have achieved notable results and can generate complete songs, yet they do not allow fine-grained user control [2–4]. Symbolic music, in contrast, enables precise\n64\tcontrol over melody, harmony, and other elements, holding\n65\ta central position in human-AI co-creation. Consequently,\n66\tthis direction continues to attract significant attention from\n67\tboth academia and industry [5].\n68\tIn recent years, researchers have drawn on language\n69\tmodels from natural language processing to capture\n70\tlong-term dependencies in music and achieve structured\n71\tmelody generation. Such methods offer an end-to-end\n72\tframework, excellent representation learning ability, and\n73\tthe potential to generate sequences of arbitrary length.\n74\t\n75\t1 The source code is available at:\n76\thttps://github.com/\n77\tKreuzter0421/RPPNet-PyTorch.git\n78\t\n79\t1\n80\t\n81\t\fThis algorithm represents a melody as a sequence of nonequidistant rhythm-pitch primitives (RPPs).\n82\tThe RPP-level stage employs decoupled serial prediction for autoregressive RPP generation, constructing longterm structure; the Note-level stage decodes RPPs into\n83\tMIDI notes via time-scale expansion mapping. Unlike barbased approaches (e.g., Museformer, MELONS), RPPNet\n84\treplaces fixed bars with perceptually-driven flexible grouping units—the first hierarchical model to do so, grounded\n85\tin psychological evidence that phrase boundaries often\n86\tmisalign with notated bar lines.\n87\tOur contributions are as follows:\n88\t1. We propose RPPNet, a two-stage hierarchical framework with a novel perception-driven structural representation. It replaces fixed bar-level boundaries\n89\twith flexible rhythm-pitch primitives grouped by\n90\tacoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity perception.\n91\t2. We propose an automatic grouping algorithm that\n92\tderives structural boundaries without explicit annotations. Controlled ablations demonstrate that performance gains stem from perceptual grouping principles rather than model capacity.\n93\t3. The proposed time-scale expansion mapping bridges\n94\tdiscrete RPP events and continuous Note-level generation, with decoupled serial prediction ensuring\n95\tstrict alignment between generated notes and the\n96\tRPP sequences.\n97\t4. Experimental results show that RPPNet outperforms\n98\texisting baselines in long-term structural coherence\n99\tand musicality.\n100\t2. RELATED WORK\n101\t2.1 Long Sequence Symbolic Music Generation\n102\tSymbolic music generation performs algorithmic composition by modeling discrete musical events, encoded\n103\tin formats including MIDI, MusicXML, and ABC notation.Early research focused on local sequential dependency\n104\tmodeling: N-gram Markov chains predict the next event\n105\tbased on joint preceding events [25], yet can only capture short-range dependencies and fail to model deep hierarchical structures. HMM introduce latent states to implicitly control token distributions [26, 27], while dynamic\n106\tBayesian networks further explicitly model deep dependencies [28].\n107\tIn recent years, deep neural network generative models have achieved significant advances in symbolic music. From RNNs [29], VAEs [30], and GANs [31], to\n108\tTransformers [32–34], modeling capabilities have steadily\n109\tincreased. However, the quadratic complexity of Transformer self-attention, compounded by the long sequence\n110\tnature of symbolic music, poses severe challenges for\n111\tmodeling dependencies spanning hundreds of bars.\n112\tThis challenge stems from standard tokenization strategies, where a single piece can reach thousands to tens of\n113\t\n114\tthousands of tokens [35], severely weakening long-term\n115\tdependency modeling [36, 37]. Even when subsequent\n116\tstudies introduce compound tokens (e.g., Compound Word\n117\t[38], Octuple [39]) to compress sequence length, models\n118\tstill struggle to capture thematic repetition and variation\n119\tspanning dozens of bars—the core difficulty of long-term\n120\tstructure modeling.\n121\t2.2 Structure modeling guided by music theory\n122\tTo address the challenges of long-range structural modeling in music, researchers have attempted to incorporate\n123\tmusic theory priors into model design to guide globally\n124\tcoherent generation. The relevant methods can be grouped\n125\tinto three categories.\n126\tStructure-aware attention: Optimizing attention distribution to efficiently extract musical structural features. For example, Museformer [15] combines fineand coarse-grained attention to capture bar-level structure; HAT [40] builds a harmony-aware hierarchical Transformer, using harmonic progressions to guide long-range\n127\tdependency modeling.\n128\tExternal structural prior injection: Explicitly introducing boundary or thematic features to constrain the generation process. Ref. [41] uses segmentation modules and\n129\tmulti-scale attention to inject structural boundary information, aiding long-form generation; Theme Transformer\n130\t[16] takes retrieved thematic material as a conditional sequence to enhance cross-segment thematic consistency.\n131\tHierarchical modeling and task decomposition: break\n132\tlong sequence generation into multi-level subtasks for\n133\tglobally controllable structure. MusicFramework [42] captures repetitive patterns via hierarchical representations\n134\tto support multi-level abstract melody generation; TMCGAN [43] explicitly models themes with a VAE-CGAN\n135\thybrid architecture, balancing global coherence and local\n136\tvariation; PhraseLDM [36] performs non-autoregressive\n137\tgeneration in a phrase-level latent space to yield 128bar multi-track music, alleviating long-term structure fragmentation. PopMNet [18] models internal dependencies\n138\tvia chord-melody graphs, while MELONS [17] combines\n139\tbar-level relational graphs with GraphRNN and Transformer for long-term structure modeling.\n140\tHowever, these methods all lack perceptual grounding\n141\tin structural segmentation. Neither explicit bar-level splitting nor implicit attention-based partitioning can capture\n142\tthe diversity and perceptual uncertainty of phrase boundaries, leading to structural degradation in long-term generation. Developing perceptually grounded, compact structural units for efficient structure-aware long-term structure\n143\tmodeling remains a core challenge.\n144\t2.3 Perceptual Theories of Musical Structure\n145\tThe challenge of modeling long-range structure in symbolic music [11–13] stems from the highly structured intrinsic nature of music: its elements are organized according to certain structural frameworks and expressed in\n146\thuman-understandable ways [14]. This framework exhibits significant multi-dimensional characteristics [44–\n147\t\n148\t\f46], encompassing not only basic components such as harmony and phrases but also interweaving cognitive organizational principles like similarity perception [21], making\n149\tthe analysis and modeling of its internal logic highly complex [47].\n150\tMusic psychology research shows that structural perception relies primarily on three mechanisms: (1) acoustic cues—using changes in intensity, pitch, duration, timbre, etc. to mark structural boundaries [20]; (2) auditory\n151\tinertia—based on the establishment and fulfillment of expectations for musical events [19]; (3) similarity perception—associating structural elements through motivic repetition and variation [21]. Together, these mechanisms reveal the hierarchical and theme-driven nature of musical\n152\tstructure.\n153\tDeliege [20] validated the psychological effectiveness\n154\tof grouping preference rules, confirming that acoustic\n155\tchanges in intensity and pitch serve as core cues for perceiving structural boundaries. Cooper and Meyer [19]\n156\tidentified auditory inertia as the organizing force of musical rhythm: listeners perceive continuous sound as a\n157\tdynamic structure based on psychological expectations,\n158\twhere deviations such as syncopation and rests create\n159\ttension. Lamont and Dibben [21] demonstrated through\n160\tcross-genre listening experiments that similarity judgments rely primarily on surface features such as texture\n161\tand pitch contour rather than deep structural assumptions,\n162\texhibiting significant contextual dependence.\n163\tTraditional music modeling is mostly based on noteor bar-level granularity, which hardly aligns with the actual mechanisms of structural perception. Drawing on\n164\tthe above psychological findings, this paper proposes\n165\ta heuristic algorithm that automatically analyzes monophonic melody structure based on acoustic cues, auditory\n166\tinertia, and similarity perception, and converts it into RPP\n167\tsequence data.\n168\t3. METHOD\n169\t3.1 Heuristic Segmentation of Rhythm-Pitch\n170\tPrimitive\n171\tTo construct cognitively grounded low-level structural\n172\tunits, we propose a heuristic melody segmentation algorithm that parses melodies into Rhythm-Pitch Primitives\n173\t(RPPs), each containing at most three notes to carry local\n174\tboundary information and support RPP-level generation,\n175\tlaying the foundation for subsequent hierarchical modeling.\n176\tPrimitives are defined by rhythmic patterns (five categories, e.g., iambic) and pitch contours (ascending, descending, etc.), as illustrated in Figure 1; evolutionary relationships between adjacent primitives are encoded via\n177\tmulti-hot vectors. Grouping employs dynamic programming to maximize the cumulative structural weight W (·) 2\n178\tof the parsed sequence (Algorithm 1), where W (·) scores\n179\t2 The complete formalization of W (·) is available in the repository\n180\t\n181\tmentioned above.\n182\t\n183\tAlgorithm 1 Dynamic Programming for RPP Grouping\n184\tInput: Note sequence P1:L , Weight function W (·)\n185\tOutput: Optimal RPP list R\n186\t1: if L ≤ 3 then\n187\t2:\n188\treturn {MakeRPP(P1:L )}\n189\t3: end if\n190\t4: dp[0] ← 0,\n191\tdp[1 . . . L] ← −∞\n192\t5: path[0 . . . L] ← ∅\n193\t6: for i = 1 to L do\n194\t7:\n195\tk ∗ ← arg max1≤k≤3 {dp[i − k] + W (Pi−k+1:i )}\n196\t8:\n197\tdp[i] ← dp[i − k ∗ ] + W (Pi−k∗ +1:i )\n198\t9:\n199\tpath[i] ← path[i − k ∗ ] ∪ {k ∗ }\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b529c00d-6edd-4686-9a76-38b1b6c81fed", "uuid": "9ab15d71-e14d-4843-a714-fce5d655e89a", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T07:45:58.682Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_review/rppnet.txt", "content": "RPPNET: PERCEPTUALLY-GROUPED RHYTHM-PITCH PRIMITIVES\nFOR LONG-TERM STRUCTURE MELODY GENERATION VIA\nBOUNDARY-AWARE MODELING\nTieyao Zhang1\nYuke Liu1\nJiaxing Yu2\n2\n2\nXinda Wu\nKejun Zhang\nGenfang Chen1,3\n1\nZhejiang Conservatory of Music, Hangzhou, China\n2\nZhejiang University, Hangzhou, China\n3\nZJU-ZJCM MusicAI Lab, Hangzhou, China\ntieyaozhang@stu.zjcm.edu.cn, keke@stu.zjcm.edu.cn, yujx@zju.edu.cn,\nwuxinda@zju.edu.cn, zhangkejun@zju.edu.cn, cgf@zjcm.edu.cn\n\narXiv:2607.19776v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n\nABSTRACT\n\nThey require no hand-crafted domain rules and can automatically extract knowledge from large-scale data; their\neffectiveness has been validated across multiple disciplines\n[6–10].\nHowever, long-term structure modeling in symbolic\nmusic remains challenging [11–13]. Existing methods\noperate within linear sequence frameworks where attention mechanisms capture long-range token correlations yet\nfail to learn explicit associations between non-adjacent\nbut functionally similar structural units; meanwhile, this\ntask requires integrating music theory, computational modeling, psychology, and neuroscience [14]. Both factors\njointly constrain effective learning of hierarchical logic, biasing models toward local statistical patterns and limiting\nlong-term structure generation quality.\nRecent works integrate computational modeling with\nmusic theory to improve long-term coherence through explicit structural boundaries and thematic features, such as\nMuseformer [15] with its hierarchical attention mechanism, Theme Transformer [16] with thematic material retrieval, and MELONS [17] and PopMNet [18] with graphstructured thematic variation encoding. However, these\nmethods rely on fixed bar-level units. Psychological evidence shows that listeners perceive structural boundaries\nthrough acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similaritybased grouping [19–21], rather than fixed metric segmentation. This mismatch hinders listeners’ perceptual grouping of the generated structure, thereby reducing overall\nmusical coherence.\nTo address this problem, we propose a hierarchical\nmelody generation framework, RPPNet 1 . It is based on\nan autoregressive architecture and splits generation into\nan RPP-level generation stage and a Note-level generation stage. Both stages use a Transformer encoder-decoder\n[22].\nDrawing on music theory and cognitive psychology,\nwe use three perceptual dimensions—acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity relations—and rhythmic structure analysis [20, 23, 24] to design a heuristic algorithm.\n\nExisting symbolic music generation models typically use\nbars as the basic structural unit. However, human perception of musical phrases often does not align with notated\nbar lines, leading to long-term structural fragmentation.\nThis paper proposes RPPNet—a two-stage deep learning\narchitecture with variable structural boundaries. It first\ngenerates variable-length Rhythm-Pitch Primitive (RPP)\nsequences, where each RPP encodes note count, rhythm,\nand contour; then decodes the RPP sequences into concrete notes. The grouping of RPPs is automatically derived\nfrom acoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity perception based on music psychology. Experiments show that\nmelodies generated by RPPNet are superior in both longterm structure and musicality, with significant improvements across all subjective evaluation dimensions. Ablation studies confirm that the performance gain stems from\nthe structural correctness of the psychological representation, rather than from model capacity. This work offers\nan interdisciplinary perspective for music generation, integrating music theory, computational modeling, and music\npsychology.\n1. INTRODUCTION\nSymbolic melody generation is a core direction of generative AI in art [1]. In recent years, text-to-audio models have achieved notable results and can generate complete songs, yet they do not allow fine-grained user control [2–4]. Symbolic music, in contrast, enables precise\ncontrol over melody, harmony, and other elements, holding\na central position in human-AI co-creation. Consequently,\nthis direction continues to attract significant attention from\nboth academia and industry [5].\nIn recent years, researchers have drawn on language\nmodels from natural language processing to capture\nlong-term dependencies in music and achieve structured\nmelody generation. Such methods offer an end-to-end\nframework, excellent representation learning ability, and\nthe potential to generate sequences of arbitrary length.\n\n1 The source code is available at:\nhttps://github.com/\nKreuzter0421/RPPNet-PyTorch.git\n\n1\n\n\fThis algorithm represents a melody as a sequence of nonequidistant rhythm-pitch primitives (RPPs).\nThe RPP-level stage employs decoupled serial prediction for autoregressive RPP generation, constructing longterm structure; the Note-level stage decodes RPPs into\nMIDI notes via time-scale expansion mapping. Unlike barbased approaches (e.g., Museformer, MELONS), RPPNet\nreplaces fixed bars with perceptually-driven flexible grouping units—the first hierarchical model to do so, grounded\nin psychological evidence that phrase boundaries often\nmisalign with notated bar lines.\nOur contributions are as follows:\n1. We propose RPPNet, a two-stage hierarchical framework with a novel perception-driven structural representation. It replaces fixed bar-level boundaries\nwith flexible rhythm-pitch primitives grouped by\nacoustic cues, auditory inertia, and similarity perception.\n2. We propose an automatic grouping algorithm that\nderives structural boundaries without explicit annotations. Controlled ablations demonstrate that performance gains stem from perceptual grouping principles rather than model capacity.\n3. The proposed time-scale expansion mapping bridges\ndiscrete RPP events and continuous Note-level generation, with decoupled serial prediction ensuring\nstrict alignment between generated notes and the\nRPP sequences.\n4. Experimental results show that RPPNet outperforms\nexisting baselines in long-term structural coherence\nand musicality.\n2. RELATED WORK\n2.1 Long Sequence Symbolic Music Generation\nSymbolic music generation performs algorithmic composition by modeling discrete musical events, encoded\nin formats including MIDI, MusicXML, and ABC notation.Early research focused on local sequential dependency\nmodeling: N-gram Markov chains predict the next event\nbased on joint preceding events [25], yet can only capture short-range dependencies and fail to model deep hierarchical structures. HMM introduce latent states to implicitly control token distributions [26, 27], while dynamic\nBayesian networks further explicitly model deep dependencies [28].\nIn recent years, deep neural network generative models have achieved significant advances in symbolic music. From RNNs [29], VAEs [30], and GANs [31], to\nTransformers [32–34], modeling capabilities have steadily\nincreased. However, the quadratic complexity of Transformer self-attention, compounded by the long sequence\nnature of symbolic music, poses severe challenges for\nmodeling dependencies spanning hundreds of bars.\nThis challenge stems from standard tokenization strategies, where a single piece can reach thousands to tens of\n\nthousands of tokens [35], severely weakening long-term\ndependency modeling [36, 37]. Even when subsequent\nstudies introduce compound tokens (e.g., Compound Word\n[38], Octuple [39]) to compress sequence length, models\nstill struggle to capture thematic repetition and variation\nspanning dozens of bars—the core difficulty of long-term\nstructure modeling.\n2.2 Structure modeling guided by music theory\nTo address the challenges of long-range structural modeling in music, researchers have attempted to incorporate\nmusic theory priors into model design to guide globally\ncoherent generation. The relevant methods can be grouped\ninto three categories.\nStructure-aware attention: Optimizing attention distribution to efficiently extract musical structural features. For example, Museformer [15] combines fineand coarse-grained attention to capture bar-level structure; HAT [40] builds a harmony-aware hierarchical Transformer, using harmonic progressions to guide long-range\ndependency modeling.\nExternal structural prior injection: Explicitly introducing boundary or thematic features to constrain the generation process. Ref. [41] uses segmentation modules and\nmulti-scale attention to inject structural boundary information, aiding long-form generation; Theme Transformer\n[16] takes retrieved thematic material as a conditional sequence to enhance cross-segment thematic consistency.\nHierarchical modeling and task decomposition: break\nlong sequence generation into multi-level subtasks for\nglobally controllable structure. MusicFramework [42] captures repetitive patterns via hierarchical representations\nto support multi-level abstract melody generation; TMCGAN [43] explicitly models themes with a VAE-CGAN\nhybrid architecture, balancing global coherence and local\nvariation; PhraseLDM [36] performs non-autoregressive\ngeneration in a phrase-level latent space to yield 128bar multi-track music, alleviating long-term structure fragmentation. PopMNet [18] models internal dependencies\nvia chord-melody graphs, while MELONS [17] combines\nbar-level relational graphs with GraphRNN and Transformer for long-term structure modeling.\nHowever, these methods all lack perceptual grounding\nin structural segmentation. Neither explicit bar-level splitting nor implicit attention-based partitioning can capture\nthe diversity and perceptual uncertainty of phrase boundaries, leading to structural degradation in long-term generation. Developing perceptually grounded, compact structural units for efficient structure-aware long-term structure\nmodeling remains a core challenge.\n2.3 Perceptual Theories of Musical Structure\nThe challenge of modeling long-range structure in symbolic music [11–13] stems from the highly structured intrinsic nature of music: its elements are organized according to certain structural frameworks and expressed in\nhuman-understandable ways [14]. This framework exhibits significant multi-dimensional characteristics [44–\n\n\f46], encompassing not only basic components such as harmony and phrases but also interweaving cognitive organizational principles like similarity perception [21], making\nthe analysis and modeling of its internal logic highly complex [47].\nMusic psychology research shows that structural perception relies primarily on three mechanisms: (1) acoustic cues—using changes in intensity, pitch, duration, timbre, etc. to mark structural boundaries [20]; (2) auditory\ninertia—based on the establishment and fulfillment of expectations for musical events [19]; (3) similarity perception—associating structural elements through motivic repetition and variation [21]. Together, these mechanisms reveal the hierarchical and theme-driven nature of musical\nstructure.\nDeliege [20] validated the psychological effectiveness\nof grouping preference rules, confirming that acoustic\nchanges in intensity and pitch serve as core cues for perceiving structural boundaries. Cooper and Meyer [19]\nidentified auditory inertia as the organizing force of musical rhythm: listeners perceive continuous sound as a\ndynamic structure based on psychological expectations,\nwhere deviations such as syncopation and rests create\ntension. Lamont and Dibben [21] demonstrated through\ncross-genre listening experiments that similarity judgments rely primarily on surface features such as texture\nand pitch contour rather than deep structural assumptions,\nexhibiting significant contextual dependence.\nTraditional music modeling is mostly based on noteor bar-level granularity, which hardly aligns with the actual mechanisms of structural perception. Drawing on\nthe above psychological findings, this paper proposes\na heuristic algorithm that automatically analyzes monophonic melody structure based on acoustic cues, auditory\ninertia, and similarity perception, and converts it into RPP\nsequence data.\n3. METHOD\n3.1 Heuristic Segmentation of Rhythm-Pitch\nPrimitive\nTo construct cognitively grounded low-level structural\nunits, we propose a heuristic melody segmentation algorithm that parses melodies into Rhythm-Pitch Primitives\n(RPPs), each containing at most three notes to carry local\nboundary information and support RPP-level generation,\nlaying the foundation for subsequent hierarchical modeling.\nPrimitives are defined by rhythmic patterns (five categories, e.g., iambic) and pitch contours (ascending, descending, etc.), as illustrated in Figure 1; evolutionary relationships between adjacent primitives are encoded via\nmulti-hot vectors. Grouping employs dynamic programming to maximize the cumulative structural weight W (·) 2\nof the parsed sequence (Algorithm 1), where W (·) scores\n2 The complete formalization of W (·) is available in the repository\n\nmentioned above.\n\nAlgorithm 1 Dynamic Programming for RPP Grouping\nInput: Note sequence P1:L , Weight function W (·)\nOutput: Optimal RPP list R\n1: if L ≤ 3 then\n2:\nreturn {MakeRPP(P1:L )}\n3: end if\n4: dp[0] ← 0,\ndp[1 . . . L] ← −∞\n5: path[0 . . . L] ← ∅\n6: for i = 1 to L do\n7:\nk ∗ ← arg max1≤k≤3 {dp[i − k] + W (Pi−k+1:i )}\n8:\ndp[i] ← dp[i − k ∗ ] + W (Pi−k∗ +1:i )\n9:\npath[i] ← path[i − k ∗ ] ∪ {k ∗ }", "numLines": 200, "startLine": 0, "totalLines": 790}}}
