{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-867670be4ff76cca", "type": "tool_result", "content": "200\tpath[i] ← path[i − k ∗ ] ∪ {k ∗ }\n201\t10: end for\n202\t11: R ← ∅,\n203\tidx ← 1\n204\t12: for k ∈ path[L] do\n205\t13:\n206\tR ← R ∪ {MakeRPP(Pidx:idx+k−1 )}\n207\t14:\n208\tidx ← idx + k\n209\t15: end for\n210\t16: return R\n211\t\n212\teach note based on its metrical grid position, duration, and\n213\tsyncopation pattern.\n214\t3.2 Hierarchical Sequence Representation\n215\tTo overcome self-attention dilution in long sequences [15],\n216\twe propose a hierarchical generation architecture that\n217\tstrictly decouples the RPP-level and Note-level.\n218\t3.2.1 RPP-Level Representation\n219\tWe model the global structure as a sequence of RhythmPitch Primitives. The sequence is V = {v1 , . . . , vT }. Each\n220\tunit is explicitly defined as vi = {bi , pi , di , ri , mi }, where\n221\tbi , pi , and di denote the measure index, metrical position,\n222\tand duration respectively. The rhythmic pattern ri and\n223\tmelodic contour mi characterize the motif. This abstraction achieves significant temporal downsampling, enabling\n224\tefficient identification of form development without external priors.\n225\t3.2.2 Note-Level Representation\n226\tTo realize the RPP-level representation as Note-level outputs, we define a note sequence U = {u1 , . . . , uK } mapping to final MIDI events. Each unit uj = {bj , pj , dj , nj }\n227\tshares the aforementioned temporal grid, while nj explicitly defines the absolute pitch.\n228\t3.2.3 Compound Word Embedding Strategy\n229\tExtending the Compound Word parallel fusion concept\n230\t[48], the discrete attributes within vi and uj are independently mapped into dense vectors at each time step. These\n231\tvectors are subsequently aggregated into a unified hidden\n232\trepresentation via concatenation and linear projection.\n233\t3.3 Model\n234\tAs shown in Figure 2, our two-stage hierarchical generation framework decouples melody construction into RPPlevel structural planning and Note-level instantiation. This\n235\t\n236\t\fFigure 1. Example of RPP grouping (excerpt from Hey Jude). Colored legends indicate rhythmic types; black arrows\n237\tdenote melodic contour direction.\n238\tEqn (1):\n239\t\n240\tRPP<sos>\n241\tinput\n242\t\n243\tP (vt |h<t ) = P (post |h<t ) · P (dt , rt , mt |h<t , post ) (1)\n244\t\n245\tRPP-Level Generation\n246\t\n247\tLinear\n248\t\n249\tConcat\n250\t\n251\tGlobal Position\n252\t\n253\tLinear\n254\tDetails\n255\toutput\n256\t\n257\tRPP<sos>\n258\t\n259\tRPP1\n260\t\n261\tRPP2\n262\t\n263\t......\n264\t\n265\tRPPi\n266\t\n267\tNote<sos>\n268\t\n269\tinput\n270\t\n271\tinput\n272\t\n273\t3.3.2 Note-Level Generation\n274\t\n275\tNote-Level Generation\n276\toutput\n277\t\n278\tNote<sos>\n279\t\n280\tNote1\n281\t\n282\tThe model first predicts post solely from h<t . This position representation is subsequently mapped into a temporal\n283\tprior embedding and concatenated with h<t , enabling the\n284\tjoint prediction of duration, rhythmic pattern, and melodic\n285\tcontour under explicit temporal constraints.\n286\t\n287\tNote2\n288\t\n289\t......\n290\t\n291\tNotej\n292\t\n293\tFigure 2. The architecture of the proposed two-stage hierarchical generation framework. Melody construction is\n294\tstrictly decoupled into RPP-level structural planning and\n295\tNote-level note instantiation. The dashed box details the\n296\tdecoupled serial prediction mechanism deployed at the\n297\toutput end.\n298\t\n299\tmulti-resolution temporal representation effectively addresses the semantic disparity between abstract structural\n300\tdevelopment and Note-level symbolic generation.\n301\t3.3.1 RPP-Level Generation\n302\tThe RPP-level structural module aims to generate a longterm framework guiding musical development, featuring a\n303\tstandard Transformer encoder-decoder architecture as its\n304\tcore [34].\n305\tWhile employing compound representation inputs to\n306\tcompress sequence length, we replace traditional parallel\n307\tprediction with a decoupled serial prediction mechanism\n308\tat the output, highlighted by the dashed box in Figure 2.\n309\tGiven historical context features h<t at time step t, the\n310\tjoint probability of primitive vt is strictly decoupled into\n311\tthe marginal probability of temporal position post and conditional probabilities of detailed attributes, formulated in\n312\t\n313\tThe Note-level module decodes the RPP sequence into\n314\tconcrete note events via a Transformer encoder-decoder\n315\t[34]. We construct a time-scale expansion mapping that\n316\tbridges discrete RPP events and the continuous note-level\n317\ttime axis: for each primitive i, the absolute onset is computed as Tstart = bi × Rbar + pi , and its hidden state hi is\n318\tbroadcast across all grid steps within [Tstart , Tstart + di ).\n319\tThis allows the decoder to attend to structural memory via\n320\tcross-attention, ensuring strict alignment between output\n321\tnotes and the RPP-level skeleton.\n322\t4. EXPERIMENT\n323\t4.1 Dataset\n324\tWe adopt the MelodyNet dataset [49], comprising over\n325\t300,000 MIDI melodies from FreeMIDI, HookTheory,\n326\tBitMIDI, MuseScore, KernScores, and Kunstderfuge. After removing non-melody tracks and incomplete data,\n327\t274,300 melodies remain, split into train/validation/test\n328\tsets at a ratio of 18 : 1 : 1.\n329\t4.2 Compared Models\n330\tTo evaluate the structural awareness of RPPNet, we select two representative baseline models, human-composed\n331\tmelodies, and two framework variants to validate the specific contribution of the proposed heuristic RPP grouping:\n332\t• Museformer [15]: A long-sequence music generation model with fine- and coarse-grained attention.\n333\t\n334\t\f• MELONS [17]: A graph-sequence architecture that\n335\tmodels bar-level chord and melodic contours via line\n336\tgraphs to condition token generation.\n337\t• RPPNet-Real: A variant using ground-truth RPP sequences as RPP-level input, representing the theoretical ceiling of Note-level generation.\n338\t• RPPNet-Random-Grouped: An ablation baseline replacing heuristic RPP grouping with random segmentation while maintaining architectural consistency and length distribution alignment.\n339\tWe select Museformer [15] and MELONS [17] as primary baselines, as both exemplify fixed bar-level structural modeling — the exact assumption our work relaxes. MelodyGLM [49] is excluded because its pretrainfinetune paradigm confounds structural boundary design\n340\twith large-scale pretraining. PhraseLDM [36] is excluded\n341\tas it requires explicit phrase-level annotations unavailable\n342\tin MelodyNet. Our ablation baseline RPPNet-RandomGrouped isolates the contribution of perceptual semantics\n343\tfrom mere variable-length grouping, yielding a clean controlled comparison: fixed-bar (Museformer, MELONS)\n344\tvs. perceptually-grouped variable-length (RPPNet) vs.\n345\trandomly-grouped variable-length (ablation).\n346\t4.3 Experiment Setup\n347\t4.3.1 Objective Metrics\n348\tTo validate the effectiveness of RPP grouping, we construct a random-grouping baseline (Random-Grouped) that\n349\tpreserves the length distribution of the RPP training set via\n350\trandom sampling while removing structural semantics.\n351\tFollowing Museformer [15], we adopt Perplexity (PPL)\n352\tand Structural Error (SE) as objective metrics. This alignment isolates the effect of structural representation choice\n353\tfrom metric selection bias. PPL requires a consistent vocabulary across models, so Museformer and MELONS are\n354\texcluded from the objective comparison. We also note\n355\tgrowing evidence questioning the perceptual validity of\n356\tconventional symbolic music objective metrics [50].\n357\tWe further verify the RPP-level generator’s learning of\n358\tunderlying distributions by comparing attribute statistics\n359\tbetween ground-truth and generated RPP sequences.\n360\t4.3.2 Subjective Metrics\n361\tFollowing [49], we conduct a subjective listening test with\n362\t15 paid participants (7 with musical background, 8 without) rating generated melodies on a 10-point scale (1—10).\n363\tAll models are trained from scratch, yielding 50 32-bar\n364\tmelodies evaluated across five configurations—RPPNet,\n365\tRPPNet-Real, RPPNet-Random-Grouped, Museformer,\n366\tand MELONS—alongside 10 human-composed references from the test set.\n367\tParticipants were asked to rate each melody on a scale\n368\tof 1–10 (lowest to highest) along the following four dimensions:\n369\t• Coherence: Is the melody fluent, pleasant, and engaging?\n370\t\n371\t• Rhythmicity: Does the melody exhibit a regular metric pattern and appropriate use of rests?\n372\t• Structure: Does the melody display clear structural\n373\tfeatures, such as reasonable repetition and motivic\n374\tdevelopment?\n375\t• Overall Impression: A holistic evaluation of the\n376\tmelody.\n377\tWe select Museformer [15] and MELONS [17] as primary baselines, both representing fixed bar-level structural modeling that our work relaxes. MelodyGLM\n378\t[49] is excluded as its pretrain-finetune paradigm introduces a confounding variable unrelated to boundary\n379\tdesign. PhraseLDM [36] is excluded due to its reliance on explicit phrase annotations unavailable in MelodyNet. The ablation baseline RPPNet-Random-Grouped\n380\tisolates perceptual semantics from variable-length grouping alone, enabling a controlled comparison across fixedbar, perceptually-grouped, and randomly-grouped conditions.\n381\t5. RESULT\n382\t5.1 Statistic Analysis\n383\tTo quantify RPP-level distributional fidelity, we statistically compare real and generated attribute distributions,\n384\tyielding a Pearson correlation of 92.19% across 23 categories (Table 2). Dimension-level analysis reveals strong\n385\talignment in note group (r = 0.98) and melodic contour\n386\t(r = 0.90), while rhythm pattern shows the largest gap\n387\t(r = 0.44), primarily due to over-generation of iambs (0,1:\n388\t+15.5%) and under-generation of trochees (1,0: −11.4%).\n389\tThese results suggest the model effectively captures note\n390\tgrouping and pitch contour structure, while rhythmic pattern fidelity remains the primary direction for improvement.\n391\t5.2 Ablation Study\n392\tTo validate the effectiveness of heuristic RPP grouping, we\n393\tconstruct a random-grouping ablation baseline (RandomGrouped) within the RPPNet framework with aligned\n394\tlength distribution. Objective metrics (Table 3) show that\n395\tstandard RPPNet (P P L = 2.21, SE = 0.0132) outperforms Random-Grouped (2.36, 0.0175).\n396\tSubjective evaluation (Table 1) further reveals that\n397\tRandom-Grouped exhibits significant degradation across\n398\tall dimensions upon removing heuristic grouping: coherence (5.99, p<0.001), rhythmic quality (6.08, p < 0.01),\n399\tstructural quality (6.01, p < 0.001), and overall impression (6.09, p < 0.01). This demonstrates that the structural semantics captured by heuristic grouping are critical\n400\tfor melodic coherence and motif organization.\n401\tMeanwhile, standard RPPNet and RPPNet-Real\n402\t(ground-truth RPP input) show no significant difference\n403\tin coherence (6.61 vs. 6.61, p = 1.00), rhythmic quality\n404\t(6.61 vs. 6.59, p = 0.93), or overall impression (6.69 vs.\n405\t6.61, p = 0.55), with structural quality also approaching\n406\t\n407\t\fModel\n408\t\n409\tCoherence\n410\t\n411\tRhythmicity\n412\t∗∗\n413\t\n414\tHuman\n415\t\n416\t7.29 ± 0.74\n417\t\n418\tRPPNet (Ours)\n419\tRPPNet-Real\n420\tRPPNet-Rnd-Grp\n421\tMuseformer [15]\n422\tMELONS [17]\n423\t\n424\t6.61 ± 0.71\n425\t6.61 ± 0.85\n426\t5.99 ± 0.62∗∗∗\n427\t5.81 ± 0.54∗∗∗\n428\t5.39 ± 0.69∗∗∗\n429\t\n430\tStructure\n431\t\n432\t∗∗\n433\t\n434\tOverall\n435\t\n436\t7.36 ± 0.68\n437\t\n438\t∗∗\n439\t\n440\t7.45 ± 0.82\n441\t\n442\t7.47 ± 0.79∗∗\n443\t\n444\t6.61 ± 0.69\n445\t6.59 ± 0.83\n446\t6.08 ± 0.54∗∗\n447\t5.62 ± 0.53∗∗∗\n448\t5.33 ± 0.66∗∗∗\n449\t\n450\t6.77 ± 0.73\n451\t6.51 ± 0.98\n452\t6.01 ± 0.64∗∗∗\n453\t5.57 ± 0.58∗∗∗\n454\t5.31 ± 0.76∗∗∗\n455\t\n456\t6.69 ± 0.68\n457\t6.61 ± 0.87\n458\t6.09 ± 0.66∗∗\n459\t5.73 ± 0.54∗∗∗\n460\t5.30 ± 0.77∗∗∗\n461\t\n462\tTable 1. Results of the subjective evaluation. Scores are presented as Mean ± Standard Deviation. Asterisks denote\n463\tsignificant differences compared to our proposed RPPNet (∗∗ p < 0.01, ∗∗∗ p < 0.001). “Overall” denotes the overall\n464\tmusical impression.\n465\tAttribute / Pattern\n466\t\n467\tReal (%)\n468\t\n469\tGenerated (%)\n470\t\n471\tNote Group\n472\tOne note\n473\tTwo notes\n474\tThree notes\n475\t\n476\t12.26\n477\t36.25\n478\t51.49\n479\t\n480\t10.61\n481\t40.41\n482\t48.98\n483\t\n484\tRhythm Pattern\n485\t(0,)\n486\t(1,)\n487\t(0, 1)\n488\t(1, 0)\n489\t(0, 0, 1)\n490\t(0, 1, 0)\n491\t(1, 0, 0)\n492\t\n493\t7.74\n494\t4.51\n495\t14.29\n496\t21.96\n497\t14.14\n498\t17.72\n499\t19.64\n500\t\n501\t8.43\n502\t2.19\n503\t29.83\n504\t10.57\n505\t16.31\n506\t17.18\n507\t15.49\n508\t\n509\tMelodic Contour\n510\tDescending\n511\tAscending\n512\tStationary\n513\tCont. Descending\n514\tCont. Ascending\n515\tCont. Stationary\n516\tDown then Up\n517\tUp then Down\n518\tStay then Up\n519\tStay then Down\n520\tDown then Stay\n521\tUp then Stay\n522\tSingle Note\n523\t\n524\t15.47\n525\t13.18\n526\t7.60\n527\t7.68\n528\t7.26\n529\t6.32\n530\t8.93\n531\t10.11\n532\t2.85\n533\t3.30\n534\t2.51\n535\t2.54\n536\t12.26\n537\t\n538\t15.15\n539\t18.19\n540\t7.06\n541\t6.83\n542\t6.28\n543\t3.25\n544\t8.91\n545\t8.15\n546\t4.46\n547\t3.98\n548\t3.74\n549\t3.39\n550\t10.61\n551\t\n552\tTable 2. Detailed statistical distributions of note density,\n553\trhythm pattern, and melodic contour across real and generated datasets.\n554\tnon-significance (6.77 vs. 6.51, p = 0.08). This suggests\n555\tthat the RPP-level generator of RPPNet possesses strong\n556\tdistribution fitting capabilities, corroborating the findings\n557\tfrom statistical experiments.\n558\t5.3 Comparison with Previous Models\n559\tTable 1 presents the subjective ratings and significance\n560\ttests against baselines. Human-composed melodies score\n561\t7.47 overall as the reference ceiling. RPPNet achieves\n562\tan overall impression of 6.69, significantly outperforming Museformer (5.73, p < 0.001) and Melons (5.30,\n563\tp < 0.001). The advantage is most pronounced in structural quality: RPPNet (6.77) exceeds Museformer (5.57,\n564\tp < 0.001) and MELONS (5.31, p < 0.001) by 1.20 and\n565\t1.46 points, respectively, demonstrating that explicit hierarchical structural modeling effectively enhances the organization of long-term structure.\n566\t\n567\tModel\n568\t\n569\tPPL ↓\n570\t\n571\tSE ↓\n572\t\n573\tRPPNet (Ours)\n574\tRPPNet-Random-Grouped\n575\t\n576\t2.21\n577\t2.36\n578\t\n579\t0.0132 ± 0.0013\n580\t0.0175 ± 0.0008\n581\t\n582\tTable 3. Results of the objective evaluation in the ablation\n583\tstudy. SE denotes the structural entropy of Rhythmic Pattern Primitives (RPPs). The best results are highlighted in\n584\tbold.\n585\t6. DISCUSSION\n586\tThis work integrates music-psychological principles with\n587\tmusic theory to propose RPPNet, a perception-driven\n588\tstructural representation for melody generation that transcends fixed bar-level boundaries through hierarchical decoupled generation. Experiments confirm that this framework significantly outperforms existing baselines in longterm structural coherence and overall musicality.\n589\tThese results demonstrate that perception-driven grouping significantly outperforms fixed bar-level representations. Ablation experiments reveal that performance gains\n590\tstem from the proper encoding of perceptual grouping\n591\tprinciples—merely breaking bar isometry without respecting perceptual rules yields no benefit.\n592\tAlthough RPPNet significantly outperforms existing\n593\tbaselines, a quality gap remains compared to human compositions (overall 7.47vs.6.69), likely attributable to the\n594\tdistributional mismatch in rhythmic patterns (Pearson r =\n595\t0.44). Closing this gap is the central challenge going forward.\n596\tFuture work will proceed along three directions: (1)\n597\thybrid data-driven and rule-driven structural strategies;\n598\t(2) introducing micro-macro feedback mechanisms where\n599\tNote-level generation revises RPP-level structure; and (3)\n600\textending this representation to polyphonic music and accompaniment generation, evaluating its capability under\n601\tcomplex musical textures.\n602\t7. REFERENCES\n603\t[1] S. Ji, X. Yang, and J. Luo, “A survey on deep learning\n604\tfor symbolic music generation: Representations, algorithms, evaluations, and challenges,” ACM Computing\n605\tSurveys, vol. 56, no. 1, pp. 1–39, 2023.\n606\t[2] J. Copet, F. Kreuk, I. Gat, T. Remez, D. Kant, G. Synnaeve, Y. Adi, and A. Défossez, “Simple and control-\n607\t\n608\t\flable music generation,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 36, pp. 47 704–47 720,\n609\t2023.\n610\t[3] J. Liang, H. Zhang, H. Liu, Y. Cao, Q. Kong,\n611\tX. Liu, W. Wang, M. D. Plumbley, H. Phan,\n612\tand E. Benetos, “Wavcraft: Audio editing and\n613\tgeneration with large language models,” in ICLR 2024\n614\tWorkshop on LLM Agents, 2024. [Online]. Available:\n615\thttps://openreview.net/forum?id=xJw7x2ZBex\n616\t[4] H. Liu, Z. Chen, Y. Yuan, X. Mei, X. Liu, D. Mandic,\n617\tW. Wang, and M. D. Plumbley, “Audioldm: Text-toaudio generation with latent diffusion models,” arXiv\n618\tpreprint arXiv:2301.12503, 2023.\n619\t[5] J.-P. Briot and F. Pachet, “Deep learning for music generation: Challenges and directions,” Neural Computing\n620\tand Applications, vol. 32, no. 4, pp. 981–993, 2020.\n621\t[6] H. C.-Z. Anna, V. Ashish, U. Jakob, S. Ian, H. Curtis,\n622\tS. Noam, D. Monica, E. Douglas et al., “Music transformer: Generating music with long-term structure,”\n623\tarXiv preprint, 2018.\n624\t[7] J. Jumper, R. Evans, A. Pritzel, T. Green, M. Figurnov, O. Ronneberger, K. Tunyasuvunakool, R. Bates,\n625\tA. Žídek, A. Potapenko et al., “Highly accurate protein\n626\tstructure prediction with AlphaFold,” nature, vol. 596,\n627\tno. 7873, pp. 583–589, 2021.\n628\t\n629\t[14] R. Bader, Springer Handbook of Systematic Musicology. Springer, 2018.\n630\t[15] B. Yu, P. Lu, R. Wang, W. Hu, X. Tan, W. Ye, S. Zhang,\n631\tT. Qin, and T.-Y. Liu, “Museformer: Transformer with\n632\tfine-and coarse-grained attention for music generation,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 35, pp. 1376–1388, 2022.\n633\t[16] Y.-J. Shih, S.-L. Wu, F. Zalkow, M. Müller, and Y.-H.\n634\tYang, “Theme transformer: Symbolic music generation with theme-conditioned transformer,” IEEE Transactions on Multimedia, vol. 25, pp. 3495–3508, 2022.\n635\t[17] Y. Zou, P. Zou, Y. Zhao, K. Zhang, R. Zhang, and\n636\tX. Wang, “Melons: Generating melody with long-term\n637\tstructure using transformers and structure graph,” in\n638\tICASSP 2022-2022 IEEE International Conference on\n639\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP).\n640\tIEEE, 2022, pp. 191–195.\n641\t[18] J. Wu, X. Liu, X. Hu, and J. Zhu, “PopMNet: Generating structured pop music melodies using neural networks,” Artificial Intelligence, vol. 286, p. 103303,\n642\t2020.\n643\t[19] G. W. Cooper, G. Cooper, and L. B. Meyer, The Rhythmic Structure of Music. University of Chicago press,\n644\t1963.\n645\t\n646\t[8] N. Li, S. Liu, Y. Liu, S. Zhao, and M. Liu, “Neural\n647\tspeech synthesis with transformer network,” in Proceedings of the AAAI Conference on Artificial Intelligence, vol. 33, 2019, pp. 6706–6713.\n648\t\n649\t[20] I. Deliege, “Grouping conditions in listening to music:\n650\tAn approach to Lerdahl & Jackendoff’s grouping preference rules,” Music perception, vol. 4, no. 4, pp. 325–\n651\t359, 1987.\n652\t\n653\t[9] P. Schwaller, B. Hoover, J.-L. Reymond, H. Strobelt, and T. Laino, “Extraction of organic chemistry\n654\tgrammar from unsupervised learning of chemical reactions,” Science Advances, vol. 7, no. 15, p. eabe4166,\n655\t2021.\n656\t\n657\t[21] A. Lamont and N. Dibben, “Motivic structure and the\n658\tperception of similarity,” Music Perception, vol. 18,\n659\tno. 3, pp. 245–274, 2001.\n660\t\n661\t[10] J. M. J. Valanarasu, P. Oza, I. Hacihaliloglu, and V. M.\n662\tPatel, “Medical transformer: Gated axial-attention for\n663\tmedical image segmentation,” in International Conference on Medical Image Computing and ComputerAssisted Intervention. Springer, 2021, pp. 36–46.\n664\t\n665\t[22] Y. Ren, J. He, X. Tan, T. Qin, Z. Zhao, and T.-Y. Liu,\n666\t“Popmag: Pop music accompaniment generation,” in\n667\tProceedings of the 28th ACM International Conference\n668\ton Multimedia, 2020, pp. 1198–1206.\n669\t[23] J. Edworthy, “Interval and contour in melody processing,” Music Perception, vol. 2, no. 3, pp. 375–388,\n670\t1985.\n671\t\n672\t[11] F. Carnovalini and A. Rodà, “Computational creativity and music generation systems: An introduction to\n673\tthe state of the art,” Frontiers in Artificial Intelligence,\n674\tvol. 3, p. 14, 2020.\n675\t\n676\t[24] ——, “Pitch and contour in music processing.” Psychomusicology: A Journal of Research in Music Cognition, vol. 2, no. 1, p. 44, 1982.\n677\t\n678\t[12] Y. Ma, A. Øland, A. Ragni, B. M. Del Sette, C. Saitis,\n679\tC. Donahue, C. Lin, C. Plachouras, E. Benetos, E. Shatri et al., “Foundation models for music: A survey,”\n680\tarXiv preprint arXiv:2408.14340, 2024.\n681\t\n682\t[25] F. P. Brooks, A. L. Hopkins, P. G. Neumann, and W. V.\n683\tWright, “An experiment in musical composition,” IRE\n684\tTransactions on Electronic Computers, no. 3, pp. 175–\n685\t182, 1957.\n686\t\n687\t[13] Z. Yin, F. Reuben, S. Stepney, and T. Collins, “Deep\n688\tlearning’s shallow gains: A comparative evaluation of\n689\talgorithms for automatic music generation,” Machine\n690\tLearning, vol. 112, no. 5, pp. 1785–1822, 2023.\n691\t\n692\t[26] P. Mavromatis, “A hidden Markov model of melody\n693\tproduction in Greek church chant,” Computing in musicology: a directory of research, no. 14, pp. 93–112,\n694\t2006.\n695\t\n696\t\f[27] ——, “HMM Analysis of Musical Structure: Identification of Latent Variables Through Topology-Sensitive\n697\tModel Selection,” in International Conference on\n698\tMathematics and Computation in Music. Springer,\n699\t2009, pp. 205–217.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b529c00d-6edd-4686-9a76-38b1b6c81fed", "uuid": "dee6e2c1-ff4c-4a42-a63f-4392313dc735", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T07:47:12.859Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_review/rppnet.txt", "content": "path[i] ← path[i − k ∗ ] ∪ {k ∗ }\n10: end for\n11: R ← ∅,\nidx ← 1\n12: for k ∈ path[L] do\n13:\nR ← R ∪ {MakeRPP(Pidx:idx+k−1 )}\n14:\nidx ← idx + k\n15: end for\n16: return R\n\neach note based on its metrical grid position, duration, and\nsyncopation pattern.\n3.2 Hierarchical Sequence Representation\nTo overcome self-attention dilution in long sequences [15],\nwe propose a hierarchical generation architecture that\nstrictly decouples the RPP-level and Note-level.\n3.2.1 RPP-Level Representation\nWe model the global structure as a sequence of RhythmPitch Primitives. The sequence is V = {v1 , . . . , vT }. Each\nunit is explicitly defined as vi = {bi , pi , di , ri , mi }, where\nbi , pi , and di denote the measure index, metrical position,\nand duration respectively. The rhythmic pattern ri and\nmelodic contour mi characterize the motif. This abstraction achieves significant temporal downsampling, enabling\nefficient identification of form development without external priors.\n3.2.2 Note-Level Representation\nTo realize the RPP-level representation as Note-level outputs, we define a note sequence U = {u1 , . . . , uK } mapping to final MIDI events. Each unit uj = {bj , pj , dj , nj }\nshares the aforementioned temporal grid, while nj explicitly defines the absolute pitch.\n3.2.3 Compound Word Embedding Strategy\nExtending the Compound Word parallel fusion concept\n[48], the discrete attributes within vi and uj are independently mapped into dense vectors at each time step. These\nvectors are subsequently aggregated into a unified hidden\nrepresentation via concatenation and linear projection.\n3.3 Model\nAs shown in Figure 2, our two-stage hierarchical generation framework decouples melody construction into RPPlevel structural planning and Note-level instantiation. This\n\n\fFigure 1. Example of RPP grouping (excerpt from Hey Jude). Colored legends indicate rhythmic types; black arrows\ndenote melodic contour direction.\nEqn (1):\n\nRPP<sos>\ninput\n\nP (vt |h<t ) = P (post |h<t ) · P (dt , rt , mt |h<t , post ) (1)\n\nRPP-Level Generation\n\nLinear\n\nConcat\n\nGlobal Position\n\nLinear\nDetails\noutput\n\nRPP<sos>\n\nRPP1\n\nRPP2\n\n......\n\nRPPi\n\nNote<sos>\n\ninput\n\ninput\n\n3.3.2 Note-Level Generation\n\nNote-Level Generation\noutput\n\nNote<sos>\n\nNote1\n\nThe model first predicts post solely from h<t . This position representation is subsequently mapped into a temporal\nprior embedding and concatenated with h<t , enabling the\njoint prediction of duration, rhythmic pattern, and melodic\ncontour under explicit temporal constraints.\n\nNote2\n\n......\n\nNotej\n\nFigure 2. The architecture of the proposed two-stage hierarchical generation framework. Melody construction is\nstrictly decoupled into RPP-level structural planning and\nNote-level note instantiation. The dashed box details the\ndecoupled serial prediction mechanism deployed at the\noutput end.\n\nmulti-resolution temporal representation effectively addresses the semantic disparity between abstract structural\ndevelopment and Note-level symbolic generation.\n3.3.1 RPP-Level Generation\nThe RPP-level structural module aims to generate a longterm framework guiding musical development, featuring a\nstandard Transformer encoder-decoder architecture as its\ncore [34].\nWhile employing compound representation inputs to\ncompress sequence length, we replace traditional parallel\nprediction with a decoupled serial prediction mechanism\nat the output, highlighted by the dashed box in Figure 2.\nGiven historical context features h<t at time step t, the\njoint probability of primitive vt is strictly decoupled into\nthe marginal probability of temporal position post and conditional probabilities of detailed attributes, formulated in\n\nThe Note-level module decodes the RPP sequence into\nconcrete note events via a Transformer encoder-decoder\n[34]. We construct a time-scale expansion mapping that\nbridges discrete RPP events and the continuous note-level\ntime axis: for each primitive i, the absolute onset is computed as Tstart = bi × Rbar + pi , and its hidden state hi is\nbroadcast across all grid steps within [Tstart , Tstart + di ).\nThis allows the decoder to attend to structural memory via\ncross-attention, ensuring strict alignment between output\nnotes and the RPP-level skeleton.\n4. EXPERIMENT\n4.1 Dataset\nWe adopt the MelodyNet dataset [49], comprising over\n300,000 MIDI melodies from FreeMIDI, HookTheory,\nBitMIDI, MuseScore, KernScores, and Kunstderfuge. After removing non-melody tracks and incomplete data,\n274,300 melodies remain, split into train/validation/test\nsets at a ratio of 18 : 1 : 1.\n4.2 Compared Models\nTo evaluate the structural awareness of RPPNet, we select two representative baseline models, human-composed\nmelodies, and two framework variants to validate the specific contribution of the proposed heuristic RPP grouping:\n• Museformer [15]: A long-sequence music generation model with fine- and coarse-grained attention.\n\n\f• MELONS [17]: A graph-sequence architecture that\nmodels bar-level chord and melodic contours via line\ngraphs to condition token generation.\n• RPPNet-Real: A variant using ground-truth RPP sequences as RPP-level input, representing the theoretical ceiling of Note-level generation.\n• RPPNet-Random-Grouped: An ablation baseline replacing heuristic RPP grouping with random segmentation while maintaining architectural consistency and length distribution alignment.\nWe select Museformer [15] and MELONS [17] as primary baselines, as both exemplify fixed bar-level structural modeling — the exact assumption our work relaxes. MelodyGLM [49] is excluded because its pretrainfinetune paradigm confounds structural boundary design\nwith large-scale pretraining. PhraseLDM [36] is excluded\nas it requires explicit phrase-level annotations unavailable\nin MelodyNet. Our ablation baseline RPPNet-RandomGrouped isolates the contribution of perceptual semantics\nfrom mere variable-length grouping, yielding a clean controlled comparison: fixed-bar (Museformer, MELONS)\nvs. perceptually-grouped variable-length (RPPNet) vs.\nrandomly-grouped variable-length (ablation).\n4.3 Experiment Setup\n4.3.1 Objective Metrics\nTo validate the effectiveness of RPP grouping, we construct a random-grouping baseline (Random-Grouped) that\npreserves the length distribution of the RPP training set via\nrandom sampling while removing structural semantics.\nFollowing Museformer [15], we adopt Perplexity (PPL)\nand Structural Error (SE) as objective metrics. This alignment isolates the effect of structural representation choice\nfrom metric selection bias. PPL requires a consistent vocabulary across models, so Museformer and MELONS are\nexcluded from the objective comparison. We also note\ngrowing evidence questioning the perceptual validity of\nconventional symbolic music objective metrics [50].\nWe further verify the RPP-level generator’s learning of\nunderlying distributions by comparing attribute statistics\nbetween ground-truth and generated RPP sequences.\n4.3.2 Subjective Metrics\nFollowing [49], we conduct a subjective listening test with\n15 paid participants (7 with musical background, 8 without) rating generated melodies on a 10-point scale (1—10).\nAll models are trained from scratch, yielding 50 32-bar\nmelodies evaluated across five configurations—RPPNet,\nRPPNet-Real, RPPNet-Random-Grouped, Museformer,\nand MELONS—alongside 10 human-composed references from the test set.\nParticipants were asked to rate each melody on a scale\nof 1–10 (lowest to highest) along the following four dimensions:\n• Coherence: Is the melody fluent, pleasant, and engaging?\n\n• Rhythmicity: Does the melody exhibit a regular metric pattern and appropriate use of rests?\n• Structure: Does the melody display clear structural\nfeatures, such as reasonable repetition and motivic\ndevelopment?\n• Overall Impression: A holistic evaluation of the\nmelody.\nWe select Museformer [15] and MELONS [17] as primary baselines, both representing fixed bar-level structural modeling that our work relaxes. MelodyGLM\n[49] is excluded as its pretrain-finetune paradigm introduces a confounding variable unrelated to boundary\ndesign. PhraseLDM [36] is excluded due to its reliance on explicit phrase annotations unavailable in MelodyNet. The ablation baseline RPPNet-Random-Grouped\nisolates perceptual semantics from variable-length grouping alone, enabling a controlled comparison across fixedbar, perceptually-grouped, and randomly-grouped conditions.\n5. RESULT\n5.1 Statistic Analysis\nTo quantify RPP-level distributional fidelity, we statistically compare real and generated attribute distributions,\nyielding a Pearson correlation of 92.19% across 23 categories (Table 2). Dimension-level analysis reveals strong\nalignment in note group (r = 0.98) and melodic contour\n(r = 0.90), while rhythm pattern shows the largest gap\n(r = 0.44), primarily due to over-generation of iambs (0,1:\n+15.5%) and under-generation of trochees (1,0: −11.4%).\nThese results suggest the model effectively captures note\ngrouping and pitch contour structure, while rhythmic pattern fidelity remains the primary direction for improvement.\n5.2 Ablation Study\nTo validate the effectiveness of heuristic RPP grouping, we\nconstruct a random-grouping ablation baseline (RandomGrouped) within the RPPNet framework with aligned\nlength distribution. Objective metrics (Table 3) show that\nstandard RPPNet (P P L = 2.21, SE = 0.0132) outperforms Random-Grouped (2.36, 0.0175).\nSubjective evaluation (Table 1) further reveals that\nRandom-Grouped exhibits significant degradation across\nall dimensions upon removing heuristic grouping: coherence (5.99, p<0.001), rhythmic quality (6.08, p < 0.01),\nstructural quality (6.01, p < 0.001), and overall impression (6.09, p < 0.01). This demonstrates that the structural semantics captured by heuristic grouping are critical\nfor melodic coherence and motif organization.\nMeanwhile, standard RPPNet and RPPNet-Real\n(ground-truth RPP input) show no significant difference\nin coherence (6.61 vs. 6.61, p = 1.00), rhythmic quality\n(6.61 vs. 6.59, p = 0.93), or overall impression (6.69 vs.\n6.61, p = 0.55), with structural quality also approaching\n\n\fModel\n\nCoherence\n\nRhythmicity\n∗∗\n\nHuman\n\n7.29 ± 0.74\n\nRPPNet (Ours)\nRPPNet-Real\nRPPNet-Rnd-Grp\nMuseformer [15]\nMELONS [17]\n\n6.61 ± 0.71\n6.61 ± 0.85\n5.99 ± 0.62∗∗∗\n5.81 ± 0.54∗∗∗\n5.39 ± 0.69∗∗∗\n\nStructure\n\n∗∗\n\nOverall\n\n7.36 ± 0.68\n\n∗∗\n\n7.45 ± 0.82\n\n7.47 ± 0.79∗∗\n\n6.61 ± 0.69\n6.59 ± 0.83\n6.08 ± 0.54∗∗\n5.62 ± 0.53∗∗∗\n5.33 ± 0.66∗∗∗\n\n6.77 ± 0.73\n6.51 ± 0.98\n6.01 ± 0.64∗∗∗\n5.57 ± 0.58∗∗∗\n5.31 ± 0.76∗∗∗\n\n6.69 ± 0.68\n6.61 ± 0.87\n6.09 ± 0.66∗∗\n5.73 ± 0.54∗∗∗\n5.30 ± 0.77∗∗∗\n\nTable 1. Results of the subjective evaluation. Scores are presented as Mean ± Standard Deviation. Asterisks denote\nsignificant differences compared to our proposed RPPNet (∗∗ p < 0.01, ∗∗∗ p < 0.001). “Overall” denotes the overall\nmusical impression.\nAttribute / Pattern\n\nReal (%)\n\nGenerated (%)\n\nNote Group\nOne note\nTwo notes\nThree notes\n\n12.26\n36.25\n51.49\n\n10.61\n40.41\n48.98\n\nRhythm Pattern\n(0,)\n(1,)\n(0, 1)\n(1, 0)\n(0, 0, 1)\n(0, 1, 0)\n(1, 0, 0)\n\n7.74\n4.51\n14.29\n21.96\n14.14\n17.72\n19.64\n\n8.43\n2.19\n29.83\n10.57\n16.31\n17.18\n15.49\n\nMelodic Contour\nDescending\nAscending\nStationary\nCont. Descending\nCont. Ascending\nCont. Stationary\nDown then Up\nUp then Down\nStay then Up\nStay then Down\nDown then Stay\nUp then Stay\nSingle Note\n\n15.47\n13.18\n7.60\n7.68\n7.26\n6.32\n8.93\n10.11\n2.85\n3.30\n2.51\n2.54\n12.26\n\n15.15\n18.19\n7.06\n6.83\n6.28\n3.25\n8.91\n8.15\n4.46\n3.98\n3.74\n3.39\n10.61\n\nTable 2. Detailed statistical distributions of note density,\nrhythm pattern, and melodic contour across real and generated datasets.\nnon-significance (6.77 vs. 6.51, p = 0.08). This suggests\nthat the RPP-level generator of RPPNet possesses strong\ndistribution fitting capabilities, corroborating the findings\nfrom statistical experiments.\n5.3 Comparison with Previous Models\nTable 1 presents the subjective ratings and significance\ntests against baselines. Human-composed melodies score\n7.47 overall as the reference ceiling. RPPNet achieves\nan overall impression of 6.69, significantly outperforming Museformer (5.73, p < 0.001) and Melons (5.30,\np < 0.001). The advantage is most pronounced in structural quality: RPPNet (6.77) exceeds Museformer (5.57,\np < 0.001) and MELONS (5.31, p < 0.001) by 1.20 and\n1.46 points, respectively, demonstrating that explicit hierarchical structural modeling effectively enhances the organization of long-term structure.\n\nModel\n\nPPL ↓\n\nSE ↓\n\nRPPNet (Ours)\nRPPNet-Random-Grouped\n\n2.21\n2.36\n\n0.0132 ± 0.0013\n0.0175 ± 0.0008\n\nTable 3. Results of the objective evaluation in the ablation\nstudy. SE denotes the structural entropy of Rhythmic Pattern Primitives (RPPs). The best results are highlighted in\nbold.\n6. DISCUSSION\nThis work integrates music-psychological principles with\nmusic theory to propose RPPNet, a perception-driven\nstructural representation for melody generation that transcends fixed bar-level boundaries through hierarchical decoupled generation. Experiments confirm that this framework significantly outperforms existing baselines in longterm structural coherence and overall musicality.\nThese results demonstrate that perception-driven grouping significantly outperforms fixed bar-level representations. Ablation experiments reveal that performance gains\nstem from the proper encoding of perceptual grouping\nprinciples—merely breaking bar isometry without respecting perceptual rules yields no benefit.\nAlthough RPPNet significantly outperforms existing\nbaselines, a quality gap remains compared to human compositions (overall 7.47vs.6.69), likely attributable to the\ndistributional mismatch in rhythmic patterns (Pearson r =\n0.44). Closing this gap is the central challenge going forward.\nFuture work will proceed along three directions: (1)\nhybrid data-driven and rule-driven structural strategies;\n(2) introducing micro-macro feedback mechanisms where\nNote-level generation revises RPP-level structure; and (3)\nextending this representation to polyphonic music and accompaniment generation, evaluating its capability under\ncomplex musical textures.\n7. REFERENCES\n[1] S. Ji, X. Yang, and J. Luo, “A survey on deep learning\nfor symbolic music generation: Representations, algorithms, evaluations, and challenges,” ACM Computing\nSurveys, vol. 56, no. 1, pp. 1–39, 2023.\n[2] J. Copet, F. Kreuk, I. Gat, T. Remez, D. Kant, G. Synnaeve, Y. Adi, and A. Défossez, “Simple and control-\n\n\flable music generation,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 36, pp. 47 704–47 720,\n2023.\n[3] J. Liang, H. Zhang, H. Liu, Y. Cao, Q. Kong,\nX. Liu, W. Wang, M. D. Plumbley, H. Phan,\nand E. Benetos, “Wavcraft: Audio editing and\ngeneration with large language models,” in ICLR 2024\nWorkshop on LLM Agents, 2024. [Online]. Available:\nhttps://openreview.net/forum?id=xJw7x2ZBex\n[4] H. Liu, Z. Chen, Y. Yuan, X. Mei, X. Liu, D. Mandic,\nW. Wang, and M. D. Plumbley, “Audioldm: Text-toaudio generation with latent diffusion models,” arXiv\npreprint arXiv:2301.12503, 2023.\n[5] J.-P. Briot and F. Pachet, “Deep learning for music generation: Challenges and directions,” Neural Computing\nand Applications, vol. 32, no. 4, pp. 981–993, 2020.\n[6] H. C.-Z. Anna, V. Ashish, U. Jakob, S. Ian, H. Curtis,\nS. Noam, D. Monica, E. Douglas et al., “Music transformer: Generating music with long-term structure,”\narXiv preprint, 2018.\n[7] J. Jumper, R. Evans, A. Pritzel, T. Green, M. Figurnov, O. Ronneberger, K. Tunyasuvunakool, R. Bates,\nA. Žídek, A. Potapenko et al., “Highly accurate protein\nstructure prediction with AlphaFold,” nature, vol. 596,\nno. 7873, pp. 583–589, 2021.\n\n[14] R. Bader, Springer Handbook of Systematic Musicology. Springer, 2018.\n[15] B. Yu, P. Lu, R. Wang, W. Hu, X. Tan, W. Ye, S. Zhang,\nT. Qin, and T.-Y. Liu, “Museformer: Transformer with\nfine-and coarse-grained attention for music generation,” Advances in neural information processing systems, vol. 35, pp. 1376–1388, 2022.\n[16] Y.-J. Shih, S.-L. Wu, F. Zalkow, M. Müller, and Y.-H.\nYang, “Theme transformer: Symbolic music generation with theme-conditioned transformer,” IEEE Transactions on Multimedia, vol. 25, pp. 3495–3508, 2022.\n[17] Y. Zou, P. Zou, Y. Zhao, K. Zhang, R. Zhang, and\nX. Wang, “Melons: Generating melody with long-term\nstructure using transformers and structure graph,” in\nICASSP 2022-2022 IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP).\nIEEE, 2022, pp. 191–195.\n[18] J. Wu, X. Liu, X. Hu, and J. Zhu, “PopMNet: Generating structured pop music melodies using neural networks,” Artificial Intelligence, vol. 286, p. 103303,\n2020.\n[19] G. W. Cooper, G. Cooper, and L. B. Meyer, The Rhythmic Structure of Music. University of Chicago press,\n1963.\n\n[8] N. Li, S. Liu, Y. Liu, S. Zhao, and M. Liu, “Neural\nspeech synthesis with transformer network,” in Proceedings of the AAAI Conference on Artificial Intelligence, vol. 33, 2019, pp. 6706–6713.\n\n[20] I. Deliege, “Grouping conditions in listening to music:\nAn approach to Lerdahl & Jackendoff’s grouping preference rules,” Music perception, vol. 4, no. 4, pp. 325–\n359, 1987.\n\n[9] P. Schwaller, B. Hoover, J.-L. Reymond, H. Strobelt, and T. Laino, “Extraction of organic chemistry\ngrammar from unsupervised learning of chemical reactions,” Science Advances, vol. 7, no. 15, p. eabe4166,\n2021.\n\n[21] A. Lamont and N. Dibben, “Motivic structure and the\nperception of similarity,” Music Perception, vol. 18,\nno. 3, pp. 245–274, 2001.\n\n[10] J. M. J. Valanarasu, P. Oza, I. Hacihaliloglu, and V. M.\nPatel, “Medical transformer: Gated axial-attention for\nmedical image segmentation,” in International Conference on Medical Image Computing and ComputerAssisted Intervention. Springer, 2021, pp. 36–46.\n\n[22] Y. Ren, J. He, X. Tan, T. Qin, Z. Zhao, and T.-Y. Liu,\n“Popmag: Pop music accompaniment generation,” in\nProceedings of the 28th ACM International Conference\non Multimedia, 2020, pp. 1198–1206.\n[23] J. Edworthy, “Interval and contour in melody processing,” Music Perception, vol. 2, no. 3, pp. 375–388,\n1985.\n\n[11] F. Carnovalini and A. Rodà, “Computational creativity and music generation systems: An introduction to\nthe state of the art,” Frontiers in Artificial Intelligence,\nvol. 3, p. 14, 2020.\n\n[24] ——, “Pitch and contour in music processing.” Psychomusicology: A Journal of Research in Music Cognition, vol. 2, no. 1, p. 44, 1982.\n\n[12] Y. Ma, A. Øland, A. Ragni, B. M. Del Sette, C. Saitis,\nC. Donahue, C. Lin, C. Plachouras, E. Benetos, E. Shatri et al., “Foundation models for music: A survey,”\narXiv preprint arXiv:2408.14340, 2024.\n\n[25] F. P. Brooks, A. L. Hopkins, P. G. Neumann, and W. V.\nWright, “An experiment in musical composition,” IRE\nTransactions on Electronic Computers, no. 3, pp. 175–\n182, 1957.\n\n[13] Z. Yin, F. Reuben, S. Stepney, and T. Collins, “Deep\nlearning’s shallow gains: A comparative evaluation of\nalgorithms for automatic music generation,” Machine\nLearning, vol. 112, no. 5, pp. 1785–1822, 2023.\n\n[26] P. Mavromatis, “A hidden Markov model of melody\nproduction in Greek church chant,” Computing in musicology: a directory of research, no. 14, pp. 93–112,\n2006.\n\n\f[27] ——, “HMM Analysis of Musical Structure: Identification of Latent Variables Through Topology-Sensitive\nModel Selection,” in International Conference on\nMathematics and Computation in Music. Springer,\n2009, pp. 205–217.", "numLines": 500, "startLine": 200, "totalLines": 790}}}
